            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kenji Sharma\u2019s existence is a testament to the cultural confluence of San Francisco. Born in the Sunset District, he was the only child of an Indian software engineer from Mumbai and a Japanese-American florist from Japantown. His childhood home was a fragrant blend of curry powder and cherry blossoms, his meals a delightful negotiation between his father\u2019s spicy vegetarian dishes and his mother\u2019s delicate preparations of fish and rice. This fusion defined his palate and, ultimately, his destiny.\n\nAcademically, Kenji was adrift. He found little inspiration in textbooks and graduated high school with no clear path forward. At 18, needing work, he took a job as a dishwasher at a small, traditional sushi bar in Japantown. It was there, amidst the steam and clatter, that he found his calling. He watched the stoic Itamae, Mr. Watanabe, with awe. He saw the reverence in his movements, the artistry in his blade, and the quiet dignity of a lifelong craft. Kenji begged to be taught. For seven years, he was an apprentice, starting with the painstaking process of perfecting sushi rice, a task he wasn't allowed to graduate from for two full years.\n\nThe turning point came when Mr. Watanabe retired and recommended Kenji to a new, high-end restaurant opening in Hayes Valley. He excelled, his unique upbringing allowing him to subtly innovate while honoring tradition. Now, at 46, he is the Head Itamae, earning the respect of his peers and the devotion of his patrons.\n\nKenji lives alone in a simple one-bedroom apartment in the Inner Richmond. His daily routine is a ritual: a morning walk in Golden Gate Park, followed by the 5-Fulton MUNI ride to work, where he spends hours meticulously preparing for the evening service. The intense focus of the dinner rush is his meditation. His work has been his longest and most consuming relationship, leaving little time for lasting romance, though he maintains a close circle of friends from the restaurant industry.\n\nHis aspiration isn't fame, but purity. Kenji dreams of opening his own tiny, eight-seat omakase counter\u2014a quiet space where he can share his story, one perfect piece of nigiri at a time, a true reflection of the city and family that shaped him."
